Question 3

tokenized <- mt_samples %>%
  unnest_tokens(word, transcription) %>%
  anti_join(stop_words)
Joining with `by = join_by(word)`
word_counts <- tokenized %>%
  count(word, sort = TRUE)

top_20_words <- word_counts %>%
  slice_head(n = 20)

ggplot(top_20_words, aes(x = reorder(word, n), y = n)) +
  geom_col() +
  coord_flip() +
  labs(title = "Top 20",
       x = "Word",
       y = "Count")

Without the stop words you can tell more about the text.

Question 4

bi_grams <- mt_samples %>%
  unnest_tokens(bigram, transcription, token = "ngrams", n = 2) %>%
  filter(!bigram %in% stop_words$word)

bigram_counts <- bi_grams %>%
  count(bigram, sort = TRUE)

top_20_bigrams <- bigram_counts %>%
  slice_head(n = 20)

ggplot(top_20_bigrams, aes(x = reorder(bigram, n), y = n)) +
  geom_col() +
  coord_flip() +
  labs(title = "Top 20 Bi-grams",
       x = "Bi-gram",
       y = "Count")

tri_grams <- mt_samples %>%
  unnest_tokens(trigram, transcription, token = "ngrams", n = 3) %>%
  filter(!trigram %in% stop_words$word)

trigram_counts <- tri_grams %>%
  count(trigram, sort = TRUE)

top_20_trigrams <- trigram_counts %>%
  slice_head(n = 20)

ggplot(top_20_trigrams, aes(x = reorder(trigram, n), y = n)) +
  geom_col() +
  coord_flip() +
  labs(title = "Top 20 Tri-grams",
       x = "Tri-gram",
       y = "Count")

Adding the tri-grams gives you more information about the patient.

Question 7

word_counts <- mt_samples %>%
  unnest_tokens(word, transcription) %>%
  anti_join(stop_words) %>%
  group_by(medical_specialty, word) %>%
  count()
Joining with `by = join_by(word)`
specialty_word_frequencies <- word_counts %>%
  group_by(medical_specialty) %>%
  mutate(word_frequency = n / sum(n))

target_words <- c("surgical", "blood", "pain")

filtered_words <- specialty_word_frequencies %>%
  filter(word %in% target_words)

print(filtered_words)
